  "statement": {
    "ambiguity_status": "minor",
    "intended": "Construct a random graph on $n$ vertices in the following way: begin with the complete graph $K_n$. At each stage, choose uniformly a random triangle in the graph and delete all the edges of this triangle. Repeat until the graph is triangle-free.\n\nDescribe the typical parameters and structure of such a graph. In particular, if $f(n)$ is the number of edges remaining, then is it true that\\[\\mathbb{E}f(n)\\asymp n^{3/2}\\]and that $f(n) \\ll n^{3/2}$ almost surely?",
    "intended_statement_status": "source_text_pending_theorem_level_audit",
    "interpretation_branches": [],
